commit f1c662a9573a7b2aa17b1aa621e71c71f2b97d5d
Author: Babak Bandpey <bb@cocode.dk>
Date:   Thu Apr 23 20:20:55 2026 +0200

    feat: M15b-alpha — sidecar-integrated tun2socks (TCP path)
    
    Codex architecture review chose option B (sidecar-integrated) over
    gomobile AAR: keeps the existing ProcessBuilder sidecar, one Go
    runtime, no NDK. Lands in three parts:
    
    1. Kotlin TUN fd handoff
       - ParvazVpnService clears FD_CLOEXEC on the PFD's file descriptor
         via android.system.Os.fcntlInt (API 30+), then hands the raw fd
         number in the SidecarConfig JSON. ProcessBuilder fork+exec inherits
         the fd on the child side.
       - addDisallowedApplication(packageName) keeps sidecar's own outbound
         sockets outside the tunnel — no recursion loop.
       - API < 30 hard-fails with SessionState.failed() + log instead of
         silently blackholing packets (codex P2). minSdk stays at 24 so
         onboarding still works on older Androids; tun2socks is Android 11+.
       - ConnectionState + SessionState extracted to ParvazConnectionState.kt
         so ParvazVpnService.kt stays under the 200-line cap.
    
    2. Go core/tun2socks — engine runner
       - New package wraps xjasonlyu/tun2socks/v2 engine.Insert/Start/Stop,
         exposed as Runner.Start(cfg) / Wait(ctx) / Stop() so startup and
         lifecycle are separable.
       - Device = fd://<TunFD>, Proxy = socks5://127.0.0.1:<listenPort>.
       - parvazd launches the loopback SOCKS5 Accept loop first, then calls
         runner.Start synchronously BEFORE printing READY (codex review 2
         P2). If the engine's internal log.Fatalf fires, the process exits
         before READY is ever emitted — CoreLauncher reads EOF-before-READY
         as failure, so Kotlin never flips the UI to CONNECTED with the
         data plane down. Lifecycle runs on `go runner.Wait(ctx)`.
       - Adds ~7 MB to the cross-compiled libparvaz.so (gvisor tcpip
         stack). Accepted — MVP speed over binary size.
    
    3. Go core/mitm — SNI-driven leaf minting
       - tun2socks hands the interceptor an IP literal (no DNS lookup
         context), so keying the leaf on the CONNECT host as before would
         serve certs for IPs that browsers reject. Fix (codex P1):
         tls.Config.GetCertificate reads ClientHelloInfo.ServerName and
         mints the leaf for whatever SNI the browser sent. Post-handshake,
         ConnectionState().ServerName becomes the authoritative host for
         the upstream URL, so the dispatcher + relay still see real
         hostnames.
       - Keeps the existing leaf cache; cache key is whatever name arrives
         via SNI (or the fallback CONNECT host).
    
    Known gap — **blocks demo, tracked as M15b-beta in PLAN.md**:
    UDP via SOCKS5 UDP ASSOCIATE isn't implemented (core/socks5 server
    only speaks CONNECT), so tun2socks drops UDP packets — including DNS
    queries. Chrome with DoH will work; everything else won't resolve.
    Fix requires either adding UDP ASSOCIATE + a DoH resolver to parvazd,
    or intercepting UDP/53 at the tun2socks layer and answering from a
    local DNS shim. Separate PR.
    
    Test status:
    - go test ./... — all 11 packages green including tun2socks.
    - ./gradlew :app:testDebugUnitTest — green.
    - ./gradlew :app:lintDebug + :app:assembleDebug — green.
    - Cross-compile CGO_ENABLED=0 GOOS=android GOARCH=arm64 — ~17 MB
      libparvaz.so built cleanly.
    - Emulator verification — STILL PENDING. TCP browsing with Chrome+DoH
      is the next checkpoint once M15b-beta lands for DNS.
    
    Codex-review iteration 1 flagged three P1/P2 issues:
      P1a hostname loss → fixed via MITM SNI sniff (above).
      P1b UDP/DNS drop → documented as M15b-beta, not fixed this PR.
      P2 API<30 silent success → fixed with fail-fast guard.
    
    Codex-review iteration 2 flagged one more P2:
      P2 READY fired before tun2socks engine up → fixed by reordering:
        Runner split into Start/Wait, Start runs pre-READY, Wait in goroutine.
    
    Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>

